data.text:
Urban-centrism and elitism have dominated Indian cricket up till very recently, and these two are significant reasons for the lack of lower-caste cricketers. 

Interesting to see how compositions of state sides, IPL sides have changed recently, and will change as cricket expands.

Casteism in cricket is a real issue that needs proper study, not a thread of flimsy arguments. We must gather instances and experiences of lower caste cricketers at all levels and understand why there are so few lower caste cricketers.

Gavaskar's instance reinforces the point that poorer people simply don't play cricket. His quote doesn't mean "I wouldn't have been selected", it means "I simply would not have played cricket" had he been switched at birth. Caste is related only tangentially to this. https://t.co/zJkEGhaUNF
Ganguly's comment on "looking beyond surnames" is taken completely out of context: it was a sycophantic defense of a nepotistic boss, not an assertion of caste-blindness. https://t.co/BSA2H34RpL

data.text:
Have we heard of casteism against current lower castes (or Christians) in the team?

The rise of the IPL adds another dimension. How many lower caste players in the IPL? Do we think an IPL scouting team is blind to caste or not? How many have played for 'A' and LOI sides?

And lower caste cricketers are simply not managing to come in through the system.

Do we have any instances of lower caste cricketers not being selected at 'A' level, or for India sides when it was obvious they should have been?

It strikes me as very odd that no lower caste cricketer, current or ex, has ever mentioned caste bias anywhere, let alone making it an issue. 

I wonder why that is. Maybe at the higher levels, Indian cricket is post-caste in some manner? Maybe the issue lies at the lower levels+

To truly gauge casteism in Indian cricket, measure the no. of lower caste players entering the system and proportions rising up through levels. My guess is, a very low percentage of lower castes even enter the system. If they do, many must leave due to alienation/discrimination.
